## 1. Purpose
This policy defines how [COMPANY] segments and protects its networks so that systems handling PHI are isolated, exposed only as necessary, and protected from untrusted networks. It minimizes attack surface and lateral movement across the [AWS] environment.

## 2. Scope
Applies to all [AWS] VPCs, subnets, security groups, network ACLs, gateways, load balancers, [WAF], and connectivity (VPN, [PrivateLink], peering, Transit Gateway) in scope of the ISMS, and to [Snowflake] network policies. It covers production and non-production environments and any connectivity between them.

## 3. Policy
1. Networks **shall** be segmented by trust level and function (e.g., public/edge, application, data tiers) using separate subnets and security groups; PHI-bearing data stores reside in **private subnets** with no direct internet route.
2. **Production and non-production environments shall be isolated** — preferably in **separate [AWS] accounts/VPCs** — with no flat network connectivity; non-prod **shall not** contain production PHI.
3. **Security groups and NACLs shall enforce least-privilege, default-deny.** **No security group shall allow `0.0.0.0/0` ingress to databases, data stores, or other PHI-bearing/internal services**; administrative ports (SSH/RDP/DB ports) **shall not** be open to the internet.
4. Inbound internet exposure **shall** be limited to explicitly intended public endpoints (e.g., the application load balancer), fronted by a **[WAF]** and TLS termination per `cryptography-and-key-management.md.template`.
5. Private connectivity (**VPC endpoints / [PrivateLink]**) **shall** be used to reach [AWS] services and [Snowflake] where feasible, keeping traffic off the public internet.
6. Administrative/remote access to private resources **shall** be brokered through controlled paths (e.g., [SSM Session Manager], bastion, or zero-trust access) — not direct internet exposure — with MFA per `../access/access-control-policy.md.template`.
7. Network flows **shall** be logged (**VPC Flow Logs**, [WAF] logs) and monitored per `logging-and-monitoring-policy.md.template`; GuardDuty analyzes network threats.
8. All network configuration **shall** be defined as code and changed through `change-management-policy.md.template`; security-group changes that increase exposure trigger alerts.
9. [Snowflake] **shall** enforce network policies restricting access to approved IP ranges/[PrivateLink].

## 4. Roles & Responsibilities
| Role | Responsibility |
|---|---|
| [Platform Engineering Lead] | Designs and implements segmentation, security groups, WAF, and private connectivity as code. |
| [Security Officer] | Approves network architecture; oversees exposure findings and monitoring. |
| Service Owners | Request least-privilege network access; justify any new exposure. |
| [CTO] | Approves this policy and material network exceptions. |

See `../governance/roles-and-responsibilities.md.template` for full role definitions.

## 5. Segmentation Architecture
- **Account/VPC structure:** Separate accounts/VPCs for [prod], [non-prod], [shared services], [security/log-archive] (`configuration-and-hardening-standard.md.template`).
- **Subnet tiers:** Public (edge/NAT/LB) → private app → private data; PHI data stores in private data subnets only.
- **East-west controls:** Security groups scoped to source security group (not broad CIDRs); microsegmentation between tiers; default-deny NACLs as a secondary boundary.
- **Egress:** Controlled outbound via NAT/[egress filtering]; restrict egress from data tiers.

## 6. Perimeter & Edge Protection
- **[WAF]** on public endpoints with managed + custom rules (OWASP categories), logging enabled.
- **TLS** terminated at the edge with TLS [1.2]+ (`cryptography-and-key-management.md.template`); HSTS where applicable.
- DDoS protection via [AWS Shield]; rate limiting at the WAF/edge.

## 7. Exceptions
Exceptions to this policy require documented risk acceptance per `../governance/exceptions-and-waivers.md.template`, approved by the [Security Officer] and [CTO], time-bound, and recorded in the exceptions log. Any internet exposure of a data store is treated as high-risk and requires explicit approval and compensating controls.

## 8. Compliance, Monitoring & Enforcement
Compliance is verified through [AWS Config]/[Security Hub] rules (e.g., open-to-world security groups, public data stores), IaC scanning in CI, and flow-log/WAF review during internal audit. Newly opened broad ingress generates alerts and is investigated per `../resilience/incident-response-plan.md.template`. Violations are handled per `../people/hr-security-policy.md.template`.

